This project was completed as part of Group 2 assignment where the 
required model was Random Forest. The dataset used is the Breast Cancer 
Wisconsin dataset which contains 569 patient records with 30 numeric 
features derived from cell nucleus measurements such as radius, texture, 
perimeter, area and smoothness. The target variable is the diagnosis 
which classifies tumors as Malignant or Benign. Random Forest was trained 
and evaluated using accuracy, precision, recall, F1 score, ROC curve and 
5-fold cross validation. Feature importance analysis revealed that 
concave points worst, perimeter worst and radius worst are the strongest 
predictors of malignancy. The model achieved high accuracy and AUC score 
making it a reliable classifier for breast cancer detection.
